des at line 939-942), modulo/rem (line 1133-1149), and round (line 1047-1131), the code explicitly handles infinity cases.\n\n6. **Normalization** (`servo/components/style/values/mod.rs`, line 43-48): The `normalize()` function converts NaN values to 0.0.\n\n7. **C++ Overflow Protection** (`gfx/src/nsCoord.h`, line 268-288): `NSToCoordTruncClamped()` bounds-checks float/double values before converting to `nscoord` (integer type), clamping values that exceed `nscoord_MAX` or `nscoord_MIN`. This prevents integer overflow when extreme or infinite values are returned from the Rust calc resolution.\n\n8. **Layout Application** (`layout/style/ServoStyleConstsInlines.h`, line 540-543): `DefaultPercentLengthToAppUnits()` in the style namespace wraps the bounds-checking call to `NSToCoordTruncClamped()`.\n\n**Overflow Handling Details:**\nWhen CSS calc() expressions produce extreme values (approaching infinity through operations like `1.0 / 0.0` in the Invert node), or very large multiplications, the Rust code naturally produces f32 infinity values. These are then safely clamped in the C++ boundary layer via `NSToCoordTruncClamped()` before being used in layout calculations. The potential crash mentioned in the issue likely occurs if these extreme values are not properly handled during intermediate calculations or if there are edge cases in the comparison logic where infinity values don't trigger the bounds checks correctly."
